snippet.textDisplay:
I remember all these Remainers saying that when Boris Johnson opposed Parliament he was ignoring the will of the people and conveniently forgetting how Parliament ignored the referendum a direct message from the people.
A lot of people don't realize that the voter calculus in the 2017 election was very different. Back in 2017 people assumed Brexit was a settled matter and they didn't like how Theresa May and the Tories planned to govern overall. The Labour Brexit vote felt safe voting for Labour.
Now in 2019 after two Brexit delays people realized the issue of Brexit wasn't settled and many felt that the 2016 referendum wasn't being respected. The Labour Brexit vote decided to give the Tories their votes to finally settle Brexit once and for all. The Remoaners assumed all those who voted Remain would ardently fight for Remaining as they still have, but many if not most of that 48% have come to accept Brexit and have moved on. Many have even come to resent those who tried to subvert the Democratic will of the people.
We also can't forget Boris Johnson who ran a much more centrist campaign to allow Labour Brexit voters to feel more comfortable voting for the Tories. Remain Tories and LibDems could never vote for someone like Jeremy Corbyn.
This vote is the the closest you'll get to a Second Referendum and it was a clear rejection of those Remainers trying to subvert the popular will.

snippet.textDisplay:
Missed the livestream because I was working at a count. In answer to your question at 15:30, at our count we (all council employees) got paid £120 plus half a day off in lieu for doing the overnight count. For that, we had to turn up at the counting hall at about 9pm, and we left at 3.45am ... but it would have been all the same if we had had a recount and been there another three hours. Sometimes if a count goes on for an exceptionally long time then staff may get their half-day in lieu upgraded to a full day – I've had that happen where we were there until 8am on Friday morning.
Obviously, I can't speak for other councils as to how they operate.
